LETTERS TO THE EDITOR
Freshman Describes Chicago Arrest
(The following letter was
written at the request of the
Sim editor.)
To the Editor:
On Thursday. Oct. 9, 1965, I
began my crinriiial lite. On
that day, the Chicago police ar—
tested me, gave me a ride in
a daddy wagon, sent me to a
Juvenile home, and for-red are
to return to Griunell.
Bciore describing my arrest,
I'll explain why I was in Chia
eago. As most students pi‘obnr
buy know by now, 505 called
itor massive anti—war and anti.
Conspiracy trial demonstra—
tions from Oct. 8-11. I drove
to Chicago with 9 other Grin—
ucll students to observe what
would happen and to parties—
page in what I hoped would be
peaceful demonstration.
We reached Chicago at about
2 o’clock Thursday morning,
and went to the church where
our group had been instructor
to report to by the military
Weatherman fiction oi 5135.
(Although we wanted to‘facilitate in some activities at
RYM-II, the more peaceful tax—
tion oi SDS, they had sent us
no information.) We then decided to go to McCormick Semi—
mary, where all-night dishes—
signs were supposedly being
held. The discussions were re—
portable about the significance
pt that night’s street fighting
between a now hundred Weathorinen and the Chicago copy;
item tactics were also supposed
to he discussed at McCormick.
When we reached actor—
pick. we found approximately
100 Weathermen in the gym—
valium; there were no organized discussions. Finally, after
about thirty minutes, a death—
el'man who had been in the
street ﬁrating came over and
explained to us what had happened. Ills explanation evolved
into a discussion, then an argue
ment, between a couple other
Weathermen and our group
about identifies and tactics,
This was the closest I ever
came to any lighting in chicago; it I had to take sides, 1
would have fought against the
Weathermen.
At six in the morning we all
want to sleep. The women were
supposed to get up at 7:30 to
participate in a raid on an
Army induction center, to des—
troy the center and the per.
tunnel. The Grinnell women dc—
